Trustee
The trustee says the following:
 Where multiple dependants exist consistent with the sole purpose test, the trustee ought to
favour dependants who were financially dependent upon the deceased at the date of death
and would have had a reasonable expectation of regular and ongoing support from them,
into retirement had they not passed;
 For this reason it determined to pay the benefit to the only person that was financially
dependent upon the deceased at the time of his passing which was FO, the deceased‟s
spouse;
 The deceased and FO had been in a relationship for approximately 15 years;
 FO provided evidence that she and the deceased jointly owned the home they lived
together in and were jointly responsible for the mortgage and rates associated with it;
 FO also informed it that she and the deceased also shared their other day to day income
and expenses and had made retirement plans together;
 The complaint has been brought on behalf of the complainant and BK with five objection
points to its decision;
> Trustee falsely identified FO as the de facto of the deceased – it relied on the
deceased‟s death certificate, home loan statement, invoices and remittance notices
sent to FO or to FO and the deceased jointly, the deceased‟s preferred beneficiary
nomination and that LOA were granted to FO;
> The deceased was estranged from the complainant and BK and therefore they may not
be best placed to confirm or deny the existence of a spousal relationship;
> The trustee disagrees with the claim that the complainant and BK are entitled to the
death benefit, while they were the deceased‟s dependants, but there is no evidence to
support that either of them were financially dependent on the deceased;
> It considered it was not appropriate to pay the benefit to the estate where there was a
dependant with an expectation of future financial support;
> In relation to the claim that the trustee failed to consider FO as a fiduciary who has a
conflict, it considered any obligations held by the executor of an estate are their own,
the trustee is not required to determine the obligations of an LPR or to make decisions
with those obligations in mind

